<TITLE> Govt is giving rural development priority: PM </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Mar 10 (bdnews24.com) Prime minister Sheikh Hasina told parliament Wednesday that the government is placing priority on rural development. She said special measures have been taken to allocate nearly Tk 4700 crore for the development of rural infrastructure. Replying to a question raised by Lutfor Rahman of Cox's Bazar -3, she said the local government engineering department will undertake a project at a cost of Tk 4,691 crore aimed at developing roads, culverts and other infrastructures in rural areas across the country. The project, under which each parliamentary constituency will receive Tk 15 crore each through MPs' recommendations, was approved by ECNEC on Tuesday. The project is expected to be implemented during the current 2009-10 fiscal year. The local government ministry is already implementing 61 rural infrastructure projects at a cost of Tk 3,556 crore, she said. "In addition, there are 34 projects in the pipeline for infrastructure development at an estimated cost of Tk. 22,664 crore," the prime minister said. Replying to another question by Md Rahmat Ali of Gazipur-3, she said all ministries and departments have been instructed to inject momentum into the administration and deliver services to every doorstep as part of the government's commitment to build 'digital Bangladesh'. "Arrangements have been taken to open websites in all the 64 district headquarters in order to ensure that all citizens can access information", she said. Hasina told Golam Dastagir Gazi of Narayanganj-1 that the government has set aside 4.55 acres of land in Jhilmil residential area for low-income people for building flats ranging from 600 to 800 square feet. Similar projects are underway in Chittagong, Rajshahi and Khulna to cater to demands of the low- and middle-income people, she said
